A cool little jazz venue in the Waikiki area.There's parking on site. At first glance, it has a dive bar feel. It's small but intimate. There was a cover charge. Maybe about 10 tables in front of a small stage. The bartender was also the server that night. I didn't have any of the food but the alcoholic drinks were ok. The band though was really cool and I enjoyed the setting. I would definitely come back.

Delicious food. decent drinks. Fun atmosphere. Not really jazzy as I was expecting from the name though... And they have a few hidden charges that we found out when we got our receipt that aren't shown on the menu. They charge $5 for a bucket of ice (not shown on menu)  They charge $5 for green tea (which is reasonable) but the container it comes in holds 2servings...which means a refill is another 2 and the tea tastes like iitoen tea from a plastic bottle. I didn't see a sign anywhere( but there could have been one ) about karaoke being $2 a song which is minor; just that we were under the impression of it being a free open karaoke (this was probably our fault to not ask. We were just given the console with 2mics without asking). Karaoke system is the WiiU karaoke so pretty good song choices. The one mic cut in and out for a friend but was system was good overall nice and loud but good balance between song music and Mic volume.  The crowd is mostly well off Japanese people who don't care about money but that isn't a good reason to have those hidden charges in the bill.  Probably won't go back.  Also, we were one of 5other people at the start when we ordered food and the food took 30min to come out...I ordered my fries separate and still took 25min with other people not eating food...

Hey, the parking situation really sucks, dropping it one star on the hit parade but this place is awesome. Local and newly renovated hole in the wall Jazz Cafe equipped with a moderate amount of less than inspirational artwork. Went recently to experience Shakka Da Band, who at least this night was a superb Carlos Santana "tribute" or cover band. The lead guitarist, whose name escapes me was fantastic and backed up but what appeared to be located percussionist Rolando Sanchez. The food was great and the wait staff was even better. We felt very much a part of the family and well watched over by a team who worked in "concert"; get it? I crack me up. I really loved the whole experience, except maybe the State of the restrooms. And did I say the parking situation really sucks on that area? Observe the top trucks who circle like sharks. Give this place a try. I promise it's memorable.
